SECTION 2. A new section of the Public School Code is
19
enacted to read:
20
"SHORT TITLE.--Sections 2 through 6 of this act may be
21
cited as the "Special Education Act"."
22
SECTION 3. A new section of the Public School Code is
23
enacted to read:
24
"DEFINITIONS.--As used in the Special Education Act:
25 SB 64
Page 6

1 A. "deputy secretary" means the deputy secretary
2 for special education;
3 B. "dyslexia" means a specific learning disability
4 that is neurobiological in origin and characterized by
5 difficulty with accurate or fluent word recognition and poor
6 spelling and decoding abilities, which characteristics
7 typically result from a deficit in the phonological component
8 of language that is often unexpected in relation to other
9 cognitive abilities and the provision of effective classroom
10 instruction and may result in problems in reading
11 comprehension and reduced reading experience that may impede
12 the growth of vocabulary and background knowledge;
13 C. "office" means the office of special education;
14 D. "school district" includes charter schools;
15 E. "special education" means the provision of
16 services additional to, supplementary to or different from
those provided in the regular school program by a systematic
17
modification and adaptation of instructional techniques,
18
materials and equipment to meet the needs of three- and
19
four-year-old children and students with disabilities; and
20
F. "student with disabilities" means a student
21
with physical or mental impairments or specific learning
22
disabilities who, as a result of those impairments or
23
specific learning disabilities, requires special education
24
and related services in accordance with the federal
25 SB 64
Page 7

1 Individuals with Disabilities Education Act."
2 SECTION 4. A new section of the Public School Code is
3 enacted to read:
4 "OFFICE OF SPECIAL EDUCATION--CREATED--DUTIES.--
5 A. The "office of special education" is created in
6 the department. The "deputy secretary for special education"
7 shall be appointed by the secretary on the basis of education
8 and experience in special education. The deputy secretary
9 shall direct the activities of the office and shall directly
10 report to the secretary.
11 B. The office shall:
12 (1) ensure that students with disabilities
13 are provided with the same opportunity for education as
14 students without disabilities;
15 (2) verify that all students with
16 disabilities receive a free appropriate public education,
regardless of the nature or severity of the disabilities;
17
(3) ensure stability and consistency of
18
services for students with disabilities;
19
(4) develop and maintain a statewide uniform
20
online system for the formulation of individualized education
21
programs and require all school districts to use the system
22
to document services, monitor progress and ensure
23
consistency, fidelity and compliance with the federal
24
Individuals with Disabilities Education Act time lines and
25 SB 64
Page 8

1 safeguards;
2 (5) enforce laws regarding the education of
3 students with disabilities, including the federal Individuals
4 with Disabilities Education Act and the Special Education
5 Act, and monitor compliance with laws that prohibit
6 discrimination against students with disabilities; and
7 (6) consult with a committee of school
8 district superintendents and charter school head
9 administrators selected by their peers on a quarterly basis
10 to plan and implement continuous improvement measures related
11 to the systems and services provided to students with
12 disabilities throughout the state."
13 SECTION 5. Section 22-13-7 NMSA 1978 (being Laws 1972,
14 Chapter 95, Section 3, as amended) is recompiled in the
15 Special Education Act and is amended to read:
16 "SPECIAL EDUCATION--RESPONSIBILITY.--
A. The office shall make, adopt and keep current a
17
state plan for special education policy, programs and
18
standards.
19
B. The department shall set standards for
20
diagnosis and screening of and educational offerings for
21
students with disabilities in public schools, developmentally
22
delayed three- and four-year-old children and eligible
23
children in private, nonsectarian, nonprofit training centers
24
and in state institutions under the authority of the
25 SB 64
Page 9

1 secretary of health.
2 C. The department shall establish and maintain an
3 evaluation program of the system that monitors the
4 implementation and impact of all special education programs
5 for three- and four-year-old developmentally delayed children
6 and students with disabilities in the public schools. The
7 system shall be operated with the cooperation of school
8 districts. Portions of the system may be subcontracted, and
9 periodic reports regarding the efficacy of special education
10 programs for children and students with disabilities shall be
11 made to the governor and the legislative education study
12 committee.
13 D. The office shall coordinate programming related
14 to the transition of students with disabilities from
15 secondary and post-secondary education programs to employment
16 or vocational placement in accordance with the Special
Education Act."
17
SECTION 6. Section 22-13-32 NMSA 1978 (being Laws 2010,
18
Chapter 59, Section 2, as amended) is recompiled in the
19
Special Education Act and is amended to read:
20
"SUPPORTS FOR STUDENTS DISPLAYING CHARACTERISTICS OF
21
DYSLEXIA.--
22
A. Within the course of the 2019-2020 and
23
2020-2021 school years and in each subsequent school year,
24
all first grade students shall be screened for dyslexia.
25 SB 64
Page 10

1 B. A student whose dyslexia screening demonstrates
2 characteristics of dyslexia and who is having difficulty
3 learning to read, write, spell, understand spoken language or
4 express thoughts clearly shall receive appropriate classroom
5 interventions through a multilayered system of supports or be
6 referred to a student assistance team.
7 C. In accordance with department procedures for a
8 multilayered system of supports, guidelines and policies,
9 each school district shall provide timely, appropriate,
10 systematic, scientific, evidence-based interventions
11 prescribed by the student assistance team, with progress
12 monitoring to determine the student's response or lack of
13 response to interventions.
14 D. A parent of a student referred to a student
15 assistance team shall be informed of the parent's right to
16 request an initial special education evaluation at any time
during the school district's implementation of the
17
interventions prescribed by the student assistance team. If
18
the school district agrees that the student may have a
19
disability, the student assistance team shall refer the child
20
for an evaluation. The student shall be evaluated within
21
sixty days of receiving the parental consent for an initial
22
evaluation. If the school district refuses the parent's
23
request for an initial evaluation, the school district shall
24
provide written notice of the refusal to the parent,
25 SB 64
Page 11

1 including notice of the parent's right to challenge the
2 school district's decision as provided in state and federal
3 law and rules.
4 E. Within the course of the 2019-2020 and
5 2020-2021 school years, every school district shall develop
6 and implement a literacy professional development plan that
7 includes a detailed framework for structured literacy
8 training by a licensed and accredited or credentialed teacher
9 preparation provider for all elementary school teachers and
10 for training in evidence-based reading intervention for
11 reading interventionists and special education teachers
12 working with students demonstrating characteristics of
13 dyslexia or diagnosed with dyslexia. The plan shall continue
14 to be implemented each school year and may be updated as
15 necessary. The department shall provide lists of recommended
16 teacher professional development materials and opportunities
for teachers and school administrators regarding
17
evidence-based reading instruction for students at risk for
18
reading failure and displaying the characteristics of
19
dyslexia.
20
F. School districts shall train school
21
administrators and teachers who teach reading to implement
22
appropriate evidence-based reading interventions. School
23
districts shall train special education teachers to provide
24
structured literacy training for students who are identified
25 SB 64
Page 12

1 with dyslexia as a specific learning disability and who are
2 eligible for special education services.
3 G. The department shall provide technical
4 assistance for special education diagnosticians and other
5 special education professionals regarding the formal special
6 education evaluation of students suspected of having a
7 specific learning disability, such as dyslexia.
8 H. The department shall adopt rules, standards and
9 guidelines necessary to implement this section."
10 SECTION 7. TEMPORARY PROVISION--RECOMPILATION.--Section
11 22-13-8 NMSA 1978 (being Laws 2009, Chapter 162, Section 1)
12 is recompiled in the Special Education Act.
13 SECTION 8. REPEAL.--Section 22-13-6 NMSA 1978 (being
14 Laws 1972, Chapter 95, Section 2, as amended) is repealed.
15 SECTION 9. EFFECTIVE DATE.--The effective date of the
16 provisions of this act is July 1, 2026. SB 64
